{
  "texts": [
    "A preference x i x j gives rise to a constraint on the (latent) utility function f and suggests that f (x i) > f (x j), i.e., alternative x i should have a higher utility score than alternative x j.",
    "Thus, the challenge for the learner is to find a value function that is as much as possible in agreement with a set of such constraints.",
    "For object ranking, this idea has first been formalized by Tesauro (1989) under the name comparison training.",
    "He proposed a symmetric neural network architecture that can be trained with representations of two states and a training signal that indicates which of the two states is preferable.",
    "The elegance of this approach comes from the property that one can replace the two symmetric components of the network with a single network, which can subsequently provide a real-valued evaluation of single states."
  ]
}